---
layout: layouts/base.njk
title: Small Models, Measured — Model Sizes, the Right Base, and What Each Can Do
description: How to choose a local model — capability versus size, what tasks each size class can actually run, and the base-model spectrum from fully-Swiss Apertus to European and international open-weight models. With the honest limits and the compliance framing included.
faq:
  - q: Is an 8B model really good enough for German legal or clinical text?
    a: For a scoped task, usually yes — but we never ask you to take that on faith. Every engagement starts by building an evaluation set from your own documents and measuring base model, RAG, fine-tune and the combination against it. If the small model doesn't clear the bar we agree up front, you see that in the report before you spend on production. The Canton of Ticino's fine-tuned Apertus-8B runs cantonal translation in production at 94% accuracy — the pattern is real, but the evaluation decides for your task.
  - q: Can you use a non-Swiss base like Mistral or Qwen — and does the EU AI Act allow it?
    a: Yes. Apertus is our default because it's fully Swiss and the only base that publishes its training data — but if your policy allows it, a European model like Mistral or an international one like Qwen can enter the evaluation and ship if it wins, still running on your own infrastructure with weights you own. On the AI Act specifically&#58; it classifies systems by <em>use-case risk</em> and puts transparency duties on the model's <em>provider</em> — it does not restrict a base model by its country of origin. The real gate is usually your own procurement and data-governance policy, which we map with you during scoping. Not legal advice — we work alongside your compliance and legal teams.
  - q: What about reasoning-heavy work?
    a: Deep multi-hop reasoning over open-ended questions is where model size still pays. Our answer is architectural, not ideological — a small model handles the routine volume, and requests it can't handle confidently escalate to a larger open-weight model running on the same infrastructure. Nothing escalates to a cloud API. The <a class="link-underline" href="/concepts/sovereign-architecture/">sovereign runtime page</a> describes how that router works.
  - q: Doesn't fine-tuning become obsolete every time a better base model ships?
    a: The expensive assets survive model swaps. Your evaluation set, your curated training data and your retrieval corpus all carry over unchanged; re-running a LoRA fine-tune on a newer base model is days of work, not a rebuild. That's also why we stay model-agnostic — Apertus, Mistral, Llama or Qwen, whichever wins on your eval set within the tier your compliance allows.
---
